# Debugging React Input Losing Focus on Keystroke

## The Root Cause

When a nested component is **recreated on every render**, React treats it as a **new element** (different identity), causing it to **unmount → remount** the DOM node. The input loses focus because the old DOM node is destroyed.

---

## Step 1: Identify the Anti-Pattern

### ❌ The Bug — Component Defined Inside Another Component

```jsx
function ParentComponent() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState("");

  // 🔴 NEW function reference every render → React sees a NEW component type
  const SearchInput = () => (
    <input
      value={value}
      onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)}
      placeholder="Type here..."
    />
  );

  return (
    <div>
      <SearchInput />  {/* Unmounts & remounts on every render */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Why this breaks:** React uses **referential identity** to track component types. A new function on each render = a new component type = destroy old tree, build new tree.

---

### ❌ Other Common Variations

```jsx
// Bug 2: Inline component in .map()
function List({ items }) {
  const [filter, setFilter] = useState("");

  return (
    <div>
      <input value={filter} onChange={(e) => setFilter(e.target.value)} />
      {items.map((item) => {
        // 🔴 New component identity on every render
        const ItemRow = () => <li>{item.name}</li>;
        return <ItemRow key={item.id} />;
      })}
    </div>
  );
}
```

```jsx
// Bug 3: Conditional inline component
function App() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");

  // 🔴 New component created conditionally
  const Wrapper = ({ children }) => <div className="special">{children}</div>;

  return (
    <Wrapper>
      <input value={query} onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)} />
    </Wrapper>
  );
}
```

---

## Step 2: Verify With React DevTools

1. Open **React DevTools → Components**
2. Type in the input
3. Watch the component **flash/disappear** on each keystroke
4. Check the **component tree** — the key/id changes or the component vanishes

You can also add a lifecycle log to confirm:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  console.log("🟢 MOUNTED");
  return () => console.log("🔴 UNMOUNTED");
}, []);
```

If you see `🔴 UNMOUNTED → 🟢 MOUNTED` on every keystroke, you've confirmed the issue.

---

